          "body": "Esther is the only canonical book that never names God — and Esther 7 is its most theologically dense chapter. The chapter's ten verses trace a reversal so precisely engineered — the second banquet, the garden pause, the misread posture, the eunuch's perfectly-timed report, the gallows already standing — that the absence of God's name becomes the chapter's most eloquent theological statement. The author does not say 'God caused Harbonah to speak.' He simply reports that Harbonah spoke, and at the right moment. He does not say 'God turned the king's heart.' He simply reports that the king returned from the garden at the moment Haman fell on the couch. The entire structure of the book — from Vashti's removal (1:12) to Mordecai's unrecorded loyalty (2:21-23) to the sleepless night of chapter 6 — has been arranged so that when chapter 7 arrives, every piece is in place. The providence of God in Esther is not a theological claim appended to a narrative; it is the narrative's own structure, visible only to the reader who has been watching the whole story."
